  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 52.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Put up again thy sword into his",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "its",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "place.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "cmt_word",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "place.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Christ orders Peter to sheathe his sword; but the wording is peculiar, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Turn away",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἀπόστρεψον",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "thy sword",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; as if Christ would say, \"The sword is none of mine; the arm of flesh and the carnal weapon are thine; turn off thy sword from the use which thou art making of it to its proper destination, to be wielded only at God's command.\" Then he gives a motive for this injunction. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "For all they that take",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "οἱ λαβόντες",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "the sword shall perish with the sword.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "cmt_word",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "the sword shall perish with the sword.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " There is a stress on the word \"take,\" and there is an imperative force in the future, \"shall perish.\" The Lord is speaking of those who arbitrarily and presumptuously resort to violence; and he says, \"Let them feel the sword.\" The word was of wide application, and contained a universal truth; it was, in fact, a re-enactment of the primaeval law touching the sacredness of human life, and the penalty that ensues on its infringement (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 9:5, 6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). It enforced also the general lesson that violence and revenge effect no good end, and bring their own punishment. There is no prophecy here (as some suppose) of the destruction of the Jews at the hands of the Romans; nor is Christ intent on soothing Peter by the thought of the future retribution which awaited the enemies whom he was so eager to chastise. Such suggestions are arbitrary and unwarranted by the context. Matthew 26:52",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
